sentence: Crude dips amid profit-taking , relief over Hurricane Ernesto 's path .
Investing.com - Crude oil futures traded lower in Asian trading on Wednesday as Hurricane Ernesto approached the Yucatan peninsula , far to the south of the Gulf of Mexico 's many oil rigs .
Talk of central bank intervention in Europe and the U.S. sent oil gaining earlier as did a fire at a California refinery , though profit-taking sent it back down in early Asian trading .

On the New York Mercantile Exchange , light , sweet crude futures for delivery in September traded at USD93 .30 a barrel on Wednesday , down 0.09 % , off from a session high of USD93 .33 and up from an earlier session low of USD93 .20 .

Hurricane Ernesto approached coastal Belize and Mexico earlier , far south of the oil-rich northern Gulf of Mexico , though investors kept an eye on the storm 's path as it emerges on the other side of the Yucatan Peninsula and back over water , where it could gain more strength .
Oil gained earlier on talk the European Central Bank and the Federal Reserve remained poised to roll out monetary easing policies to spur recovery .

Sky-high borrowing costs in Spanish government bond auctions have spurred calls for the European Central Bank to intervene by buying bonds , which would ease fears of further European downturn that would otherwise cut into oil demand .

European Central Bank President Mario Draghi has said he has a blueprint ready to go yet details remain to be worked out , yet markets grew increasingly optimistic the ECB will intervene , possibly in tandem with eurozone bailout funds .

A Spanish request for bailout assistance could give the ECB the green light to start buying Spanish government bonds , the yields of which have repeated soared above 7 % in recent weeks , a level markets deem unsustainable .

Meanwhile the Federal Reserve has said it can not rule out rolling out a similar measure known as quantitative easing , which are bond buybacks directly from banks that weaken the dollar in exchange for more robust recovery , making oil a nicely priced asset in dollar-denominated energy exchanges .
Profit-taking and weak indicators out of Europe crimped demand for oil later .
German factory orders fell 1.7 % in June , much worse than expectations for a 1.0 % decline .
Meanwhile , Italy reported that its gross domestic product contracted by 0.7 % in the second quarter , outpacing expectations for a 0.6 % contraction .

Separately , Standard & Poor 's said it was sticking with its `` CCC '' foreign and `` C '' local currency credit ratings on Greece , but assigned a negative outlook on the country , which means more downgrades are possible .
Meanwhile , a Chevron refinery in Richmond , California pushed oil up earlier though firefighters extinguished the blaze .
On the ICE Futures Exchange , Brent oil futures for September delivery were down 0.23 % and trading at USD111 .64 a barrel , up USD18 .34 from its U.S. counterpart .
